<br>
As far as protestant and LDS faiths decreasing the hold that the Roman Catholic church has on the gov't.  I have to say that yes it does produce a more secular gov't, but through that it opens the door for the people of those countries to be able to practice freedom of religion.  Just as our(US) secular gov't opens the door for each person to practice their own religion as they will.  <br>
<br>
When any one gov't (as in the areas of 10/40) or So America in the early years controls the laws and governing body,  it does not increase the faith of the people.  True faith/religiosity comes from a choice from within, not from being forced to act a certain (religiously defined)way.<br>
<br>
I have been listening to a very interesting book on tape about Islam.  I did not know the origins of that church other than it was based on the teachings of a prophet Mohamed.  Mohamed unlike most professed prophets was also a political leader, so his teachings also encompassed how to create a political environment that benefits the soul of a good muslim.  It is intertwined.  It is part of their faith to create Muslim governments, but in the early history fof Islam, tolerance of other religions existed.  Mohamed even went outside a Christian church that he was touring to do his prayers so that his followers would not feel that they had license to desecrate that church.<br>
<br>
Just as Christians have different denominations that have interpreted the bible differently, some muslims have twisted or taken out of context the original teachings of Mohamed.<br>
<br>
So IMO I think that the clashes are inevitable and I just hope that repsect for life which is part of all faiths and non -faith philosophies can prevail.  <br>
<br>
